04676nam a22009015i 9780520964648DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20162016cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209646487 a10.1525/97805209646482doi  a(DE-B1597)519731  a(OCoLC)951625708  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aBL2016.H56 7aREL0840002bisacsh04a200.954522231 aElmore, Mark, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBecoming Religious in a Secular Age /cMark Elmore. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tIntroduction: What Is This Thing Called Religion? -- tPart One. Power: How Himachal Discovered Itself And Its Religion -- t1. Becoming Sufficiently Developed in Himachal Pradesh, or How Religion Became a Problem -- t2. God Is a Beggar: Land Reforms Create Religion as a Separate Sphere -- tPart Two. Knowledge: Making And Managing Theological Culture -- t3. Ordinary Miraculousness: Farmers and Pharmacists Practice the Science of Religion -- t4. Managing Religion: Government, Gūrs, and Gods -- tPart Three. Ethics: Becoming Religious And The Mysteries Of Being -- t5. Negotiating Religion: Normalization, Abjection, And Enrichment -- t6. Cultivating Religion Amid The Conflicting Desires Of Goats, Gods, And Government -- tAfterword: Religion Is A Verb -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aReligion is often viewed as a universally ancient element of the human inheritance, but in the Western Himalayas the community of Himachal Pradesh discovered its religion only after India became an independent secular state. Based on extensive ethnographic and archival work, Becoming Religious in a Secular Age tells the story of this discovery and how it transformed a community’s relations to its past and to its members, as well as to those outside the community. And, as Mark Elmore demonstrates, Himachali religion offers a unique opportunity to reimagine relations between religion and secularity. Elmore shows that modern secularity is not so much the eradication of religion as the very condition for its development. Showing us that to become a modern, ethical subject is to become religious, this book creatively augments our understanding of both religion and modernity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aRELIGION / Religion, Politics & State.2bisacsh  aacademic.  aarchival.  acolonialism.  acolony.  acommunity.  aconversion.  adevelopment.  aeastern religion.  aeastern world.  aethics.  aethnography.  ahimachal pradesh.  ahimalayas.  aindependence.  aindia.  aindian independence.  amodern world.  amodernity.  areligion.  areligious awakening.  areligious convert.  areligious studies.  aresearch.  ascholarly.  asecular world.  asecular.  aself discovery.  asocial studies.  atransformation.  aworld history.  aworld religion.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z97831106675470 cprintz978052029053240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052096464840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520964648423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520964648/original  a978-3-11-066754-7  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY